The GitHub MCP server is an official tool that connects AI agents and assistants to GitHub’s platform, enabling capabilities like repository management, issue tracking, and workflow automation via the Model Context Protocol [1][2]. It supports both local execution via standard input/output and remote execution via HTTP/SSE, allowing integrations across various AI hosts [1][3][4].

To configure the server for a local environment, you typically add it to your MCP host's configuration file as shown below [5]:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "github": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-github"],
      "env": {
        "GITHUB_PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN": "<YOUR_TOKEN>"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

The server allows you to toggle specific functionality using the toolsets flag to manage context size and permissions [2][6]. Remote instances require an OAuth-compliant flow or a personal access token for authentication [3].
